 Kingdom":"英國英格蘭","lifeSummary":"當Richard Del Holt於1327年出生在英國武斯特斯爾亞德利時，他的父親John Del Holte II72歲，母親Judeth Cory Coy18歲。他於1351年與Alianore Durvassel在英國武斯特斯爾亞德利結婚。他們至少是3個兒子和1個女兒的父母。他去世於1346年在英國英格蘭享年19歲。"},"zh-hans":{"1327–1346":"1327年–1346年","1335–Male":"1335年–殁","–1386":"–1386年","1329–1357":"1329年–1357年","1346–1402":"1346年–1402年","1380–1423":"1380年–1423年","–Female":"殁","–Male":"殁","1255–1317":"1255年–1317年","1310–Female":"1310年–殁","1380":"1380年","1327":"1327年","1337":"1337年","1402":"1402年","1346":"1346年","1423":"1423年","1357":"1357年","1335":"1335年","1453":"1453年","1310":"1310年","1255":"1255年","1386":"1386年","1329":"1329年","1328":"1328年","1317":"1317年","Yardley, Worcestershire, England":"英国武斯特斯爾亞德利","Sussex, England":"英国素可","England, United Kingdom":"英国英格兰","lifeSummary":"当Richard Del Holt于1327年出生在英国武斯特斯爾亞德利时，他的父亲John Del Holte II72岁，母亲Judeth Cory Coy18岁。他于1351年与Alianore Durvassel在英国武斯特斯爾亞德利结婚。他们至少是3个儿子和1个女儿的父母。他去世于1346年在英国英格兰享年19岁。"},"hr":{"1327–1346":"1327.–1346.","1335–Male":"1335–preminuo","–1386":"–1386","1329–1357":"1329–1357","1346–1402":"1346.–1402","1380–1423":"1380–1423","–Female":"preminula","–Male":"preminuo","1255–1317":"1255–1317","1310–Female":"1310–preminula","1380":"1380","1327":"1327.","1337":"1337","1402":"1402","1346":"1346.","1423":"1423","1357":"1357","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","1386":"1386","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yardley, Worcestershire, England":"Yardley, Worcestershire, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"1327–1346":"1327–1346","1335–Male":"1335–Zesnulý","–1386":"–1386","1329–1357":"1329–1357","1346–1402":"1346–1402","1380–1423":"1380–1423","–Female":"Zesnulá","–Male":"Zesnulý","1255–1317":"1255–1317","1310–Female":"1310–Zesnulá","1380":"1380","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1402":"1402","1346":"1346","1423":"1423","1357":"1357","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","1386":"1386","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yardley, Worcestershire, England":"Yardley, Worcestershire, Anglie","Sussex, England":"Sussex, Anglie","England, United Kingdom":"Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1327–1346":"1327–1346","1335–Male":"1335–Afdød","–1386":"–1386","1329–1357":"1329–1357","1346–1402":"1346–1402","1380–1423":"1380–1423","–Female":"Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","1255–1317":"1255–1317","1310–Female":"1310–Afdød","1380":"1380","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1402":"1402","1346":"1346","1423":"1423","1357":"1357","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","1386":"1386","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yardley, Worcestershire, England":"Yardley, Worcestershire, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1327–1346":"1327–1346","1335–Male":"1335–Overleden","–1386":"–1386","1329–1357":"1329–1357","1346–1402":"1346–1402","1380–1423":"1380–1423","–Female":"Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1255–1317":"1255–1317","1310–Female":"1310–Overleden","1380":"1380","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1402":"1402","1346":"1346","1423":"1423","1357":"1357","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","1386":"1386","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yardley, Worcestershire, England":"Yardley, Worcestershire, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1327–1346":"1327–1346","1335–Male":"1335–Deceased","–1386":"–1386","1329–1357":"1329–1357","1346–1402":"1346–1402","1380–1423":"1380–1423","–Female":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1255–1317":"1255–1317","1310–Female":"1310–Deceased","1380":"1380","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1402":"1402","1346":"1346","1423":"1423","1357":"1357","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","1386":"1386","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yardley, Worcestershire, England":"Yardley, Worcestershire, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Holt","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, North German, Dutch, Danish, and Norwegian: topographic name for someone who lived in or by a small wood, from Middle English, Middle Low German, Danish, and Norwegian <i>holt</i>, or a habitational name from one of the many places called with this word. In England, the surname is widely distributed, but more common in Lancashire and Yorkshire than elsewhere."],"variants":[{"name":"Hohlt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Ordell.","North German: variant of   Holt   with the additional <i>h</i> reflecting the lengthened vowel or a variant of   Hohl   with the addition of excrescent <i>-t</i>.","Scandinavian: variant of   Holt  ."]},{"name":"Holten","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Hjalmer, Lars, Nils.","Dutch (also <b>Van Holten</b>) and North German: habitational name from any of the places so called, from Low German <i>holt</i> ‘holt, copse, small wood’. There are two in the Dutch province of Overijssel and another near Oberhausen in the Rhineland.","Danish: variant of   Holt  ."]},{"name":"Holtan","meanings":["Norwegian: habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads so named, from the definite plural form of <i>holt</i> ‘small wood’ (see   Holt  )."]},{"name":"Holter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Selmer, Hilmar, Knute, Lars.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads in southeastern Norway, from the indefinite plural of <i>holt</i> ‘holt, small wood’ (see   Holt  ).","North German (also <b>Hölter</b>): habitational name for someone from any of several places in Westphalia called Hölt and Holt (see   Holt  ). Compare   Hoelter  ."]},{"name":"Holtman","meanings":["Dutch: variant of   Holt   + <i>man</i> ‘man’.","Americanized form of German   Holtmann  ."]},{"name":"Holtmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Udo, Aloys, Hans, Heinz.","North German: variant of   Holt  ."]},{"name":"Holte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Bjorg, Erik, Helmer, Hjalmer, Knute, Nels, Nordahl, Selmer, Swen, Thorvald.","North German: variant of   Holt  .","North German: habitational name from any of several places so named."]},{"name":"Hoult","meanings":["English: variant of   Holt  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]},{"name":"Del","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Colloquial pet form of   Derek  , with alteration of the exposed <i>-r</i> of the short form to <i>-l</i> (  compare  Hal   and   Tel  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Derek","meanings":["From a Low German or Dutch form of <i>Theodoric</i> (  see  Terry  ), introduced into Britain during the Middle Ages by Flemish weavers, although it was not much used until a sudden explosion of popularity in the mid 20th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":1,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":10,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Del Holt was born in 1327, in Yardley, Worcestershire, England, his father, John Del Holte II, was 72 and his mother, Judeth Cory Coy, was 18. He married Alianore Durvassel in 1351, in Yardley, Worcestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1346, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 19."},"et":{"1327–1346":"1327–1346","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","–1386":"–1386","1329–1357":"1329–1357","1346–1402":"1346–1402","1380–1423":"1380–1423","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1255–1317":"1255–1317","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1380":"1380","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1402":"1402","1346":"1346","1423":"1423","1357":"1357","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","1386":"1386","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yardley, Worcestershire, England":"Yardley, Worcestershire, Engla